      "source": "target",
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure, Bernoulli's principle is a bit like a sneaky little trick that the airfoil, the shape of a wing on a plane, uses to make the plane lift off the ground. Imagine the airfoil as a clever little goblin, bending the air around it. When the air flows over the top surface of the wing, it has to travel faster than the air flowing underneath, because the top surface is longer. This faster air on top creates lower pressure, while the slower air underneath creates higher pressure. The difference in pressure between the top and bottom of the wing is what lifts the plane off the ground, just like how a clever goblin might use a gust of wind to lift its hat off its head.",
